 MAGIC adj. 1. As yet unexplained, or too complicated to explain. (Arthur C.
Clarke once said that magic was as-yet-not-understood science.) "TTY echoing
is controlled by a large number of magic bits." "This routine magically
computes the parity of an eight-bit byte in three instructions." 2.
(Stanford) A feature not generally publicized which allows something
otherwise impossible, or a feature formerly in that category but now
unveiled. Example: The keyboard commands which override the screen-hiding
features.